    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, i'm looking at our quarterly reports for the electronics warehouse and our shrinkage numbers are way higher than usual. i need to figure out how this unexpected loss is going to mess with our inventory turnover ratio. can you show me how to factor shrinkage into that calculation?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Shrinkage, as an unexpected loss, primarily affects the *cost* of your goods, not directly the core ratio calculation itself. However, to accurately reflect the true cost of inventory you've lost, you must adjust your Cost of Goods Sold (COGS) upward to account for the missing stock. This inflated COGS will consequently lower your Inventory Turnover Ratio because the numerator (COGS) is higher relative to the average inventory value.\n\nFor a more precise view, calculate your adjusted COGS as: $\\text{Actual COGS} + \\text{Value of Shrinkage}$. Then, use that figure in the standard formula: $\\text{Inventory Turnover} = \\text{Adjusted COGS} / \\text{Average Inventory}$.",
      "source": "target",
