    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "yeah, that's what we're worried about. if it's internal, we need to figure out how to tighten things up. besides just checking cameras, what are some standard industry protocols for preventing this kind of \"vanishing\" inventory? like, how do other big distributors track these tiny parts so they don't just get swiped?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "To combat internal theft of high-value small parts, implementing stricter procedural controls is key. You should explore using cycle counting more frequently and randomly, rather than relying solely on large annual counts, to catch discrepancies early. Furthermore, implementing technology like serialized tracking or RFID tags on high-risk SKUs significantly increases the audit trail, making it much harder for items to \"vanish\" without being logged. Finally, reviewing access controls and job duties to separate inventory handling from reconciliation duties can reduce opportunities for internal fraud.",
      "source": "target",
